    <div class="well">
      <pubtit>Measuring local moir√© lattice heterogeneity of twisted bilayer graphene</pubtit>
      <p><img src="http://localhost:4000/images/pubpic/TBG_SL.png" class="img-responsive" width="33%" style="float: left" /></p>
      <p>Why is there so much variation in TBG devices? And are open devices more disordered than encapsulated ones? We introduce a new method to continuously map inhomogeneities of a moir√© lattice and apply it to open-device TBG to show that twist angle variation is small over areas of hundreds of nm.</p>
      <p><em>T Benschop <em>, TA de Jong</em>, P Stepanov*, Xiaobo Lu, V Stalman, SJ van der Molen, DK Efetov, MP Allan</em></p>
      <p><strong><a href="https://journals.aps.org/prresearch/abstract/10.1103/PhysRevResearch.3.013153">Phys. Rev. Research 3, 013153 (2021)</a></strong></p>
      <p class="text-danger"><strong> </strong></p>
      <p> See also <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2107.14716">arXiv:2107.14716</a></p>
    </div>
